	<h3><strong>Lights! Camera! Action!</strong></h3>
	<p>	  You know the feeling: You see bullying happen, and you think of the   perfect response&mdash;about an hour later. If only you&rsquo;d said the right thing   at the time! Or done something a little differently. Everyone&rsquo;s had   that experience&mdash;and now here&rsquo;s your chance for a &ldquo;do-over,&rdquo; to simply   rewind what just happened and create a better ending for a bullying   situation. </p>
    <p> Create a short video that shows your brilliant &ldquo;rewind&rdquo; moment. Start   with someone being bullied and show the original response. Next, film an   actor saying &ldquo;Think how different it would be if&hellip;,&rdquo; then show a   different ending&mdash;one of those great responses you wish you&rsquo;d thought of   at the time that could help put an end to bullying. That&rsquo;s it! Easy,   fun, and powerful! </p>
    <h3> <strong>Ready to go? This&rsquo;ll help:</strong></h3>
    <p><strong>Step 1. Keep it real.</strong> Imagine a bullying scenario&mdash;like the new   kid being left out of social events or someone being slammed into a   locker for being different. Bullying can be social, physical, emotional,   or even technology based, like mean texts or rumors posted on the   Internet.<br />
      <br />
      <strong>Step 2. Pick your cast and crew.</strong> Having two to five characters will work best.<br />
      <br />
      <strong>Step 3. Write a script.</strong> Keep it brief. One scene, less than two minutes   is ideal.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Set the stage by identifying characters, setting, and type of bullying that will happen.</li>
      <li>Include a bullying incident and the characters&rsquo; responses. This is the central scene that will be &ldquo;rewound.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>Include one cast member saying, &ldquo;Think how different it would be if . . .&rdquo;</li>
      <li>Rewind! Show the central scene again&mdash;but with your better ending.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Step 4. Prep and dress rehearsal. </strong> Take these final steps before filming.<br />
      <br />
      <strong>Step 5. Film</strong> Shoot your video.<br />
      <br />
      <strong>Step 6. Share</strong> Decide how you&rsquo;ll share your video with others&mdash;in the classroom, on the Web, or in other ways.<br />
